The country is targeting around 58.524 billion Egyptian Pounds ($3.33 billion) in revenues from tobacco taxes, according to a document released by the Finance Ministry to the parliament on Sunday. The government is expecting revenues of 51.452 billion Egyptian Pounds ($2.93 billion) from the tobacco taxes this financial year, which ends in June. Egypt has been increasing taxes and cutting subsidies to narrow its budget deficit as part of economic reforms tied to a $12 billion International Monetary Fund programme aimed at boosting the economy. ($1 = 17.57 Egyptian Pounds) --Reuters--